===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|it|dilettante}}, prop. present participle of {{m|it|dilettare||to delight}}, from {{der|en|la|dēlectāre||to delight}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/dɪləˈtɒnti/}}
** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-dilettante.wav|Audio (UK)}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/ˈdɪlɪˌtɑnt/}}
** {{audio|en|En-us-dilettante.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|dilettanti|s}}

# An [[amateur]], someone who [[dabble]]s in a field out of casual interest rather than as a profession or serious interest.
#: {{syn|en|amateur|dabbler}}
#: {{ant|en|professional}}
# {{lb|en|sometimes|offensive}} A person with a general but [[superficial]] interest in any art or a branch of [[knowledge]].

====Usage notes====
This word is derived from Italian, not from French in which the ''-ante'' ending would be feminine. It is therefore correct for a person of any gender.

